" Name=\"TOC Heading\"></w:LsdException>\n </w:LatentStyles>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\n<style>\n /* Style Definitions */\n table.MsoNormalTable\n	{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\";\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\n	mso-style-priority:99;\n	mso-style-qformat:yes;\n	mso-style-parent:\"\";\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\n	mso-para-margin-top:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-right:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:10.0pt;\n	mso-para-margin-left:0in;\n	line-height:115%;\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\n	font-size:11.0pt;\n	font-family:\"Calibri\",\"sans-serif\";\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";\n	mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;}\n</style>\n<![endif]-->\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Heat 3/4 cup sugar and 3 tbsp water in small heavy duty\nsaucepan or skillet, over high heat; stirring it until dissolved and caramel\ncolored. Pour into bottom of a mold of 2 cups of capacity. Quickly swirl around\nbottom to coat. Set aside.</p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Boil water with sugar to make syrup, about 5 minutes. Let\nthe syrup cool, add it beaten eggs, orange juice. Pour into prepared mold, cover.</p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">In a cooker pressure with 1 1/2 cup of water put the mold\ninside close cooker, bring to full pressure on high heat. Reduce heat and cook\nfor 20 minutes. </p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Remove cooker from heat.</p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Allow to cool naturally, open cooker. </p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">To serve it pass small knife around edge of pan. Invert\nserving plate over pan. </p>\n\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Shake gently to release</p>\n	\n	',8,0,0,0,0,20,7,9,3,13,9,45,'../files/recipes/orange flan.JPG','2014-05-02 10:59:12','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(261,'Coconut Flan','	\n		<br>\n	\n	','	\n		<div>Caramel: In a mold, metal bowl or pot, place 1/2 sugar and 2 tablespoons water then mix it well. Cook this on medium heat on your stove until the sugar turns amber and caramelizes to a soft stage. Swirl the caramel around the mold totally covering the interior.</div><div><br></div><div>Whisk the whole eggs and yolks, add sweet coconut and mix well. Pour into prepared pan, and cover.</div><div><br></div><div>Bake at 350oF for 90 minutes or in the &nbsp;pressure cooker &nbsp;with 1 1/2 cup of water put the mold inside, close cooker, bring to full pressure on high heat. Reduce heat and cook for 20 minutes.</div><div><br></div><div>Remove cooker from heat. Allow to cool naturally, open cooker. Cool in the refrigerator. To serve run small knife around edge of pan, invert serving plate over pan. Shake gently to release.</div>\n	\n	',8,0,0,0,0,7,7,9,3,13,6,45,'../files/recipes/coconout flan.JPG','2014-03-14 18:26:20','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(397,'Heart Cake','	\n	','	\n		Preheat oven to 325oF.&nbsp; Coat 12 x 2 inch heart baking pan and other 9 x 2 inch heart baking pan with cooking spray, set aside.<br><br>Make syrup.<br><br>Beat butter and sugar until it is creamy, then mix the eggs yolks one at a time at a low speed. Pour the flour one a cup at a time and some rum until all the flour and&nbsp; the rum is finished.<br><br>In another bowl beat eggs white and mix into flour beater, mix for 5 minutes. Pour into pans and bake for 45 minutes or until a wooden pick inserted in center comes out clean, cool in pan on wire racks, remove from pan and pour syrup.<br><br>Syrup:<br><br>Mix 2 cups water or pineapple juice, a cups sugar, 1 tbs almond extract and boil until sugar dissolve. Syrup should cold when pouring on cake.<br><br><br>\n	\n	',16,0,0,0,0,10,13,9,9,13,6,50,'../files/recipes/heart cake.JPG','2014-03-15 01:09:58','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(398,'Ambrosia','	\n	','	\n		In a big bowl mix together coconut, small marshmallows,sour cream and cool whip and put in the refrigerator over night.<br><br>In the morning drain all fruits cans in a colander and pour in the bowl with coconut mix. Add grapes and chopped walnuts.<br><br>\n	\n	',5,0,0,0,0,28,16,9,8,14,6,15,'../files/recipes/ambrosia.JPG','2014-06-05 18:46:07','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(399,'Sugar Cookies','	\n	','	\n		Mix milk and vinegar, set aside.<br>Preheat oven to 350oF Grease baking sheet.<br><br>Cream butter and sugar. Beat in eggs, one at a time, add milk mix, vanilla. sift together flour, baking powder and blend into creamed mixture.<br><br>Put then in a refrigerate 3 hours. Roll out on lightly floured surface to 1/4 inch thickness. Cut with a 2 inch cookie cutter.<br><br>Place in baking sheet and sprinkle with sugar. Bake for 10 or 15&nbsp; minutes until golden brown.<br>\n	\n	',20,0,0,0,0,11,7,9,9,15,9,40,'../files/recipes/sugar cokies.JPG','2014-05-26 16:06:01','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(401,'Christmas Tree Cake','	\n	','	\n		Preheat oven to 325oF.&nbsp; Coat a Christmas&nbsp; tree shaped pan with cooking spray and set aside.<br><br>In medium bowl, with electric mixer prepare cake mix as directed on package and pour into pan. Bake for 30 minutes or until a wooden pick inserted in center comes out clean, cool&nbsp; pan on wire racks, remove from pan and cool in the refrigerator 4 hours.<br><br>Make a <a href=\"http://recipescookbook.org/recipe/How-to-make-Frosting-7-Minutes\" alt=\"frosting 7 minutes\"> 7 minutes frosting</a> as appear in this cookbook, and use it to frost top and side of the cool cake.<br><br>Decorate as you like.<br>\n	\n	',16,0,0,0,0,7,7,9,9,13,12,60,'../files/recipes/three cake.JPG','2014-03-13 06:28:51','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(402,'Orange Sugar Cookies','	\n	','	\n		Cream butter and sugar. Beat in eggs, one at a time. Blend in undiluted orange concentrate thawed and 1 tablespoon orange rind. Sift together flour and baking powder and blend into creamed mixture.<br><br>Wrap in waxed paper and refrigerate 3 hours. Roll out on lightly floured surface to 1/4 inch thickness. Cut with a 2 inch cookie cutter.<br><br>Place on greased baking sheet and sprinkle with&nbsp; 1/2 cup sugar mixed with 2 tbsp grated orange rind.<br><br>Bake in 375oF oven for 8 -10 minutes.<br><br>Makes 5 dozen cookies.<br>\n	\n	',20,0,0,0,0,16,13,9,9,15,6,215,'../files/recipes/eyed cookies.JPG','2014-06-04 07:10:49','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(403,'Pork with Rice','	\n	','	\n		Cut meat into medium pieces and marinate with garlic,onion, green pepper, lemon and spices for 30 minutes to 1 hour.<br><br>In a skillet with oil saute the meat until brown add marinate and cook with water until rare, traslate to a rice cooker , add washed rice, salt, yellow coloring and water until corresponding measure and cook.<br><br>When the rice is done wait 15 minutes, uncover and stir from bottom.<br><br>Serve hot.<br>\n	\n	',4,0,0,0,0,16,7,8,6,7,9,30,'../files/recipes/yellow rice with pork.JPG','2014-04-13 02:37:55','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(405,'Cole Slow','	\n	','	\n		Cut cabbage very thin slice, carrot in sliced 1/2\" thick, drain pineapple and reserve 3 tbsp. In a big bowl mix together all ingredients, add reserved juice and dressing. Combine well to mix all flavour.<br><br>Refrigerate 30 minutes before eat.<br>\n	\n	',5,0,0,1,0,40,13,7,8,10,6,20,'../files/recipes/cole slow.JPG','2014-05-22 00:40:23','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(406,'Famous Lime Pie','	\n	','Preheat oven to 300oF<br><br>Whisk together egg yolks, lime juice and condensed milk until smooth and creamy.<br>Pour mixture into pie crust. <br><br>Bake for 20 minutes. Cool completely on rack. Chill.<br><br>Decorate with cream and lime, if desired.<br>	\n	',6,0,0,0,0,11,16,9,9,13,10,30,'{$picture}','2014-04-30 18:14:28','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(410,'Mandarin Salad','	\n	','For dressing combine the oil,vinegar, orange juice, onion and garlic powder, mustard and honey in jar with airtight lid. Cover and shake to mix well; set aside.<br><br>Combine cooked cubed skinless chicken with thinly sliced celery in medium bowl. Pour dressing over chicken mixture, toss to mix well, cover and chill at least an hour or overnight.<br><br>Before serving drain mandarin orange segments can, toasted sliced almond and add then spinach or your favorite greens; add chicken mixture and toss gently<br><br>Serve and enjoy<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>P<br>	\n	',4,0,0,0,0,9,13,8,6,10,5,120,'{$picture}','2014-02-23 17:39:13','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(409,'Pound Cake','	\n	','	\n		Preheat oven to 325oF&nbsp; and grease and floured 10 inch bundt pan.<br><br>In a medium bowl place&nbsp; flour, sugar, butter, milk, eggs and vanilla (in that order) and with electric mixer beat at low speed 1 minute, stopping to scrap down sides. Beat at medium speed 2 minutes.<br><br>Pour into greased pan&nbsp; and bake for 1 hour and 30 minutes or until a wooden pick inserted in center comes out clean. Cool in pan on wire rack 10 minutes. Remove from pan to wire rack, and cool completely.<br><br>\n	\n	',12,0,0,0,0,7,16,9,9,15,9,100,'../files/recipes/pound cake.JPG','2014-04-03 23:34:53','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(417,'Spinach Dip','	\n	','	\n		Thawed and chopped spinach. <br><br>Combine all the ingredients except the bread in a bowl and mix well. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 2 hours. <br><br>Meanwhile make the bowl, use a large serrated knife to horizontally slice off the top third of the bread. Then use a small serrated knife to cut around the inside edge of the bowl, leaving a 1\" thick shell.<br><br>Score the bread into cubes and gently pull them out of the bowl. Place them on a plate so you can serve the bite-size pieces to scoop up the yummy dip.<br><br>You can fill the bowl and serve right away, or make it extra crispy and slightly browned by baking it. Place the empty bread bowl on an ungreased baking sheet and bake at 350oF for 10 minutes or until toasted.<br>\n	\n	',10,0,0,2,0,29,16,9,8,14,6,140,'[[]] ERROR: INFINITE LOOP DETECTED ON RECURSIVE REPLACEMENT $picture','2014-05-21 23:25:28','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(418,'Jambalaya','	\n	','	\n		Chop up onion, minced garlic, seeded and chopped green pepper,cut into chunks the chicken, cut chorizo into 1\" thick rounds, set aside.<br><br>Cooker rice make a rice. In large saucepan heat oil over medium heat,&nbsp; add onion, green pepper, garlic cook stirring until softened, add chicken and cook until browned on all sides. Add jambalaya seasoning stir to coat chicken and vegetables. Add chorizo and shrimp, cook stirring, add tomatoes and bring to simmer and cook until chicken and shrimp are cooked through, about 3 minutes. Stir in rice and parsley.<br><br>You can use andouille, chorizo or kielbasa sausage.<br>\n	\n	',6,0,0,0,0,10,13,8,6,7,5,35,'../files/recipes/jambalaya.JPG','2014-03-25 20:35:55','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(413,'Holiday Meringues','	\n	','Preheat oven to 225oF and line baking sheet with foil or waxed paper, set aside.<br><br>In mixing bowl at high speed, beat egg whites with cream of tartar until foamy. Add sugar 2 tablespoons at a time, beating until sugar is dissolved and whites stand in stiff peaks. Beat in vanilla and food coloring.<br><br>In the baking sheet, with spoon shape egg white mixture into six , 3\" nests using a scant 1/2 cup of mixture for each. Build up edges to form rims. <br><br>Bake until wooden toothpick inserted in rim comes out clean, about 1 to 1 1/2 hours. <br>turn off oven and let nest stand in oven with door closed until cool, about 2 hours.<br><br>Meanwhile, drain berry juice into 1 cup measure. Add enough water to make 1/2 cup. Pour into small saucepan and stir in cornstarch. Cook over medium heat, stirring, until mixture boils and thickens; remove from heat. Stir in berries. Cover and chill. Just before serving, spoon about 2 1/2tbs. berry mixture into each meringue shell.<br>	\n	',6,0,0,0,0,9,16,9,9,13,12,205,'{$picture}','2014-04-04 00:18:37','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(416,'Ajiaco','	\n	','	\n		<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\n <w:WordDocument>\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\n  <w:TrackMoves></w:TrackMoves>\n  <w:TrackFormatting>