t egg with milk. Dip filets in egg-milk mixture, then coat with bread crumbs mixture.<div><br></div><div>Bke at 450oF for 6 minutes, flip over and bake for 6 more minutes.</div><div><br></div><div>Enjoy</div>',4,0,0,1,1,40,13,8,9,8,9,15,'','2014-05-20 22:00:48',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(331,'Cheese Ball','	\n		<br>\n	\n	','	\n		Beat cream cheese until softened add chopped sweet pickles and stuffed oliver.&nbsp;<div><br></div><div>Ground almond. Form small balls with the cream cheese mixture and roll them up in the ground almond.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Place them in small paper baking cup.</div>\n	\n	',6,0,0,0,0,10,13,8,8,12,6,15,'../files/recipes/cheese ball.JPG','2014-03-22 11:18:29','',0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(332,'White Beans Casserole or Muneta','<br>\n','Wash white beans and soak in 3 cups water for 2 hours. Drain and put in a pot with 5 cups water, beef cutted in chuncks, ham and chorizo (spanish sausage). Cook in medium heat for 2 hours or until all are tender. (In a pressure cooker, cook for 25 minutes).<div><br></div><div>Drain in a colander, and with the broth and vegetables make a soup.</div><div><br></div><div>In a big skillet &nbsp;with olive oil saute shopped onion, add tomato sauce cook 2 minutes incorporate beef, ham, chorizo sliced and beans, cook for 10 minutes stirring to mix the flavors.</div><div><br></div><div>You can use beef skirt or other beef</div>\n',6,0,0,0,0,164,17,8,6,14,9,280,'../files/recipes/muÃ±eta casserole.JPG','2014-06-05 07:55:49',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(333,'Tiramisu','Among all the desserts, one of the most famous is undoubtedly the Italian Tiramisu; but its origin is highly discussed between the towns of Tuscany and Venetto. The boundary between legend and reality in the story of the arise of Italian Tiramisu is blur.<br><br>The first version relates that the people of Toscana called it â€œzuppa del ducaâ€ translated as â€œdukeâ€™s soupâ€; it first appeared as an especially dessert served for the Grand Duke of Tuscany, Cosimo III of Mediciâ€™s family. That was in the 17th century in Siena, where the duke was on an official visit from Florence. The Duke â€“a lover of luxury and sophisticated dishes- took the recipe with him to Florence where it had a great acceptance between local aristocracy. The fame acquired by the&nbsp; Tiramisu went beyond the borders of the Florence Duchy up to Venetto where it became a popular dessert among courtesans, since it was said to have aphrodisiac properties.<br><br>The second story targets the creation of&nbsp; Tiramisu in around the 50s, in the region of Venetto; precisely in one of the most visited brothels, where the \"mattresses\" gave it to her visitors and her own courtiers to accelerate libido, due to it was supposed to have aphrodisiac properties. The Mattresses used to offer it politely, as a miracle food which can \"te tira su\" (bursh you up). The equivalent word in Spanish is \"tentempie\".<br><br>Due to the difference in opinion, how to make Tiramisu becomes a challenge since in the most famous books of Italianâ€™s cuisine is not listed this recipe, perhaps because of its unclear origin. As per we know, in the year 1968 the Italian Tiramisu leaves the brothels to be prepared in the restaurants of Toula, and few years later it was completely propagate around the world.<br><br>How to make Tiramisu in the way it was originally conceived it is no a possible task now. The first recipe, which included eggs, sugar, chocolate and biscuits soaked in coffee was unfortunately lost or clouded in the many other antique Tiramisu recipes found. It is widely said in Italy only one restaurant knows how to make Tiramisu as the first created, but it is impossible to be sure.<br><br>Here we show how to make&nbsp; Tiramisu easily, with the ingredients you can find in any supermarket. The recipe includes some initial ingredients and others as cream cheese and liquor. We hope you enjoy this internationalized version of Italian Tiramisu as much as we did.<br>\n','In a large bowl, using an electric mixer with whisk attachment, beat egg yolks and sugar until thick and pale, about 5 minutes. Add mascarpone cheese and beat until smooth. Add 1 tablespoon of espresso and mix until thoroughly combined.<br><br>In a small shallow dish, add remaining espresso and rum. Dip each ladyfinger into espresso for only 5 seconds. Letting the ladyfingers soak too long will cause them to fall apart. Place the soaked ladyfinger on the bottom of a 13 by 9 inch baking dish, breaking them in half if necessary in order to fit the bottom.<br><br>Spread evenly 1/2 of the mascarpone mixture over the ladyfingers. Arrange another layer of soaked ladyfingers and top with remaining mascarpone mixture.<br><br>Cover tiramisu with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 2 hours, up to 8 hours. Before serving, sprinkle with chocolate shavings.<br>\n',8,0,0,0,0,19,10,9,8,13,9,120,'','2014-03-25 13:45:37',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(334,'Caldo Gallego (Porridge)','<br>\n','Wash white beans and soak in 3 cups cool water for 2 hours. Drain and put in a pot with 5 cups cool water, cut in chunks meat, smoke pork hocks, cover and cook for 2 hours or until all are tender (in a pressure cooker, cook for 25 minutes and reduce water to 3 cups.)<div><br></div><div>Meanwhile, peeled, cut in four, wash potatoes, collard green and add to the porridge when the meat are tender, taste the broth and add salt if necessary and cook until potatoes and collard green are tender, about 20 minutes.</div><div><br></div><div>Put some beans in a plate, mash then a little and put back in the pot and boil until thinck<br><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>You can use beef skirt or other beef.</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div>\n',4,0,0,0,0,25,17,9,6,14,9,260,'','2014-05-18 01:43:41',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(335,'Fabada (Porridge)','The fabada is traditional from Asturia and widespread in the Iberian Peninsula and part of Spanish cuisine.<br>It is considered a winter dish, full of calories; it is made with white beans, pork, cured meats such as bacon, sausages and blood sausage, with a smoky flavor. Needless to say, must be prepared only with these ingredients, because if you add others ingredients as potatoes and chards would prepare a different recipe.<br>According to scholars Fabada has a rather humble origin, taking into account rural ingredients used to prepare it, but it is believed that as a national dish in town, but have not written references to this in the literature the time.<br>A curious fact is that no one agrees on a precise date of emergence, but is estimated to have been between the sixteenth and eighteenth centuries, and has been released by the world through the process of emigration.<br>The fabada was brought to America by our ancestors that became effective disseminators of the plate, to keep their traditions and teach new generations to prepare typical fashion, despite cultural differences and culinary ingredients were in place where they arrived.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><br>\n','Soak white beans in 3 cups of cold water for 2 hours, drain, wash and put in a pot with 4 cups cold water, chorizo (spanish sausage), smoked pork neckbones, salted pork or bacon, ham, chopped onion and garlic; cover and cook in medium heat for 1 hour, then add the blood pudding , cover and cook for 2 hours or until all are tender, (in a pressure cooker cook for 25 minutes and reduce water to 3 cups) taste the broth and add salt if necessary. Peeled, wash and cut in four potatoes and add to pot and cook until tender, about 20 minutes.<div><br></div><div>Put some beans in a plate, mash then a little and put back in the pot and boil until thick.</div>\n',6,0,0,0,0,43,17,8,6,14,9,260,'../files/recipes/fabada.JPG','2014-06-01 23:17:06',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,'2014-03-12 12:00:03'),(337,'Crabmeat Salad','<br>\n','Grate 1 tsp. zest and squeeze &nbsp;2 tsp juice from lemon. In large bowl, combine lemon zest and juice with salad dressing, &nbsp;salt and pepper.Add chopped crabmeat and radishes; toss to coat.<div><br></div><div>Line serving platter with lettuce. Top with mixture and avocado slices.</div><div><br></div><div>If desired, garnish with lemon slices.</div>\n',4,0,0,0,0,15,13,8,8,10,9,10,'','2014-06-03 11:34:01',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(338,'Pepperoni Ziti','<br>','Preheat oven to 375oF. Coat &nbsp;2-qt. shallow baking dish with cooking spray. Set aside.<div><br></div><div>Cook pasta according to package directions; drain.</div><div><br></div><div>Meanwhile, combine ricotta. Parmesan and chopped parsley; reserve. Stir together marinara sauce and tomato paste; reserve 1 cup. Toss pasta with remaining sauce mixture in baking dish.</div><div><br></div><div>Cut pepperoni into 1/2 inch chunks, 2 cups. Quarter each slice of mozzarella. Arrange half of pepperoni, half ricotta mixture and half of mozzarella over pasta in baking dish. Add remaining pasta mixture; top with reserved cup sauce mixture, then remaining pepperoni, ricotta mixture and mozzarella.</div><div><br></div><div>Coat sheet of foil with cooking spray. Cover baking dish with foil, coated side down.Bake until hot and bubbling, 40 minutes. Uncover bake until cheese is lightly browned, 10 minutes.</div><div><br></div><div>Let stand 10-15 minutes before serving.</div>',8,0,0,0,0,18,10,9,9,4,9,85,'','2014-05-02 14:49:33',NULL,0,0,0,0,0,0,NULL),(339,'Pesto Trapani','<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\n <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\n  <o:RelyOnVML></o:RelyOnVML>\n  <o:AllowPNG></o:AllowPNG>\n </o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\n <w:WordDocument>\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\n  <w:TrackMoves></w:TrackMoves>\n  <w:TrackFormatting></w:TrackFormatting>\n  <w:PunctuationKerning></w:PunctuationKerning>\n  <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas></w:ValidateAgainstSchemas>\n  <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>\n  <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedCo